    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>The Steamer 1/2 past 11 o'clock Tuesday Morg.</p>
      <p>Dearest William. Here I am, sitting in the Chief-Cabin, writing. We are getting towards the River's-mouth. The day is very fine &amp; sunny, our winds fair, &amp; everything as prosperous as possible. My plans are all settled. I have secured the Coupe [accent mark over the e] of the Messagerie Royale, which leaves Boulogne at nine tomorrow morning &amp; arrives in Paris early the following morning. As I must have a night of it one way or other, I had rather have gone on tonight, but I find I cannot get my things</p>
      <p>from the Custom-House, &amp; the object of arriving in Paris 12 hours sooner is not in this case commensurate with the inconvenience of having my luggage to follow me. I find that the trouble as well as expense of hiring a carriage &amp; posting would be very considerable, &amp; the Coupe [accent mark] in all respects very preferable.--</p>
      <p>The whole of my journey from St James' Square to Paris (including the Steam-Boat) will amount to under 10..0..0, which deducting the 2 or 3 pound for my Mother's maid, leaves under 8..0..0 for me &amp; my two servants. I include the Hotel at Boulogne.-- So it is anything but ruinous.-- I am writing a vile</p>
      <p>scrawl, for tho' we have no sea yet, the doddering motion of the Steamer is very considerable. She is a very small vessel, &amp; by no means a fast one.--</p>
      <p>I was very much earlier this morning than I need have been, but this is a fault quite on the right side.--</p>
      <p>What can I say to you?-- I think scarcely anything more. I hope you will not be anxious or troubling yourself about the Avis. Nothing can be easier &amp; simpler than all the arrangements. Indeed I am only afraid there are not half difficulties or occupation enough for the busy adventurous Bird.-- I shall have nothing to do but to devote myself to the book I brought with me on Mesmerism, &amp; which I selected as the most suitable study for a</p>
      <p>very tiresome journey. As far as the agreeableness goes, Havre &amp; Rouen had been unquestionably preferable. At the same time I think I have done on the whole very well in my choice.--</p>
      <p>The Earl of Lovelace 10. St James' Square London Angleterre</p>
    </div></body>
